Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation in the eurozone is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 euro area countries, inflation was higher than expected in November, with an annual rate of inflation of 3.1% after the 2.6% in October, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts have been down to just 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not cut the key interest rate, which it believes will favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment to create an inflationary spiral.
The ECB is committed to keeping inflation below 2%, or at least close to the 2% mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in a dilemma: it must "stop" inflation in order to rule out the need for further action.
In November, the inflation rate in Germany reached a 12-year record high of 3.3%, while in Spain it rose from 3.6% to 4.1%.
The rise in inflation in the euro area is due to higher food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat prices rose 88 percent, and soybean prices also reached a record high since 1973.
The price of cooking oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil has risen 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
The ECB forecasts that inflation will rise from 2.1% to 2.5% in 2008, but expects a fall to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts expect inflation to be 3 percent over the next three to four months, but the annual average is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup identifies government crisis
After a long stagnation, Fidesz's support had grown significantly by early December, with the party having the largest base for the first time since 2002, while support for the Socialists reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
The difference is clear among party-loyal voters, thanks to the high degree of determination of the opposition supporters: more than two thirds (71%) are in favour of the MSZP compared to a fifth (20%).
The MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry barrier: they make up two per cent of the total population.
The number of party voters has increased by one percent in both camps.
Compared with the last low, general economic sentiment has continued to deteriorate - never before has the proportion of those who rate the country's economic situation as "extremely bad" been so high (41 per cent), while another 46 per cent consider it "pretty bad".
After a more hopeful outlook in spring and summer, the families are once again pessimistic about the change in their financial situation.
The majority of the population expects the situation to worsen further next year, with only one tenth expecting an improvement.
A December Gallup poll found that 71% of respondents rated the prime minister's work as "rather bad than right", a historic high.
Thirteen percent of those surveyed have great confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány in general, while the share of supporters of Viktor Orbán is 38 percent.
Some 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% mistrust of the head of the Fidesz party.
One of the indicators of political sentiment is the number of people who think that the dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be controlled without a change of government.
While 35% of voters voted to keep the government and the prime minister in office after the October riots, this figure has now fallen to just 20%, while the relative majority (33%) see the solution only in new elections.
When asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent said they would "certainly" participate, and another 20 percent would "probably" cast their vote.
By comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place on this Sunday, only 55% would "certainly" go to the polls, while another 15% would consider their participation "probable".
74% would vote against tuition, 79% against internship fees, and 84% against hospital fees.
If the group of those who "certainly" took part in the referendum were included, the shares of those who opposed tuition, internship and hospital fees would be 81, 84 and 89 per cent, respectively.
Auchan most expensive, Tesco increased by almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budapest shopping area have maintained the average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that there was no VAT increase this year.
Articles from Napi Gazdaság
In the Budapest shopping triangle, the price of the usual "Napi" Christmas basket has also risen by 16 percent this year, but all hypermarkets have recorded price increases of over HUF 1,000.
After the "swing" in food prices last December, the percentage increase has not been drastic compared with the high level it was at the beginning.
However, it is certainly a deterrent to consumers that what they paid for last year at a price far below HUF 9,000 is not available this year for even HUF 10,000.
The price of the 'Napi' basket exceeded the magic 10,000 HUF threshold by at least 91 HUF in the markets examined.
The highest price was HUF 10,573.
(In 6800 the price was HUF 6,800.)
Prices for unicum and live fish remained almost at the same level as in the previous year, while prices for turkey breast fillets, nuts and poppy seeds rose sharply.
Meal and bread prices were in line with the data of the Hungarian Central Statistical Office, but at Auchan there were 1 kg of bread oats for 139 forints.
There was no competitive price drop for the product below 200 forints.
Also surprising was the price of a two-litre bottle of Coca-Cola pledge below 200 forints, so the drink including pledge cost only 257 HUF.
Nevertheless, in this year's "Napi" shopping cart comparison, Auchan was the most expensive, and Cora the cheapest.
Our calculations show that Cora raised the prices in the "Napi" shopping cart by 15 percent compared to last year's Christmas prices, while Tesco and Auchan each raised 18 percent.
The difference between the cheapest basket of the previous year and the most expensive basket of the current year was 12%, while the increase between the cheapest basket of the previous year and the most expensive basket of the current year was 21%.
The average price increase was HUF 1,480.
The average price increase in the previous year was still HUF 1,206.00, but the VAT increase was noticeable in the prices at last Christmas.
This was the situation which affected trade: it seemed that the department stores were not able to decide correctly which price range to apply to the individual articles, since the effect of the price increase on consumer behaviour was unpredictable.
(If the trader does not plan well for the speed of a product, he may lose substantial profits in the price range which depends on the intensity of traffic.)
The increase in the price of the "Napi" basket last year was so radical due to VAT that the most expensive basket exceeded the value of 2006 by 1720 forints, whereas the price difference for the cheapest basket was only 844 forints.
This year, such extremes were not observed, as the most expensive basket cost 1,630.00 forints more than the previous year, and even the cheapest one had a price increase of 1,284.00 forints.
Compared with the last two Christmas seasons, prices have risen catastrophically, with the price of everyday consumer goods in hypermarkets rising by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This again does not necessarily confirm the data of the Hungarian Central Statistical Office: for some basic foodstuffs, the Statistical Office recorded an increase in price of more than 30% over a period of 12 months.
So, in addition to flour, eggs are also used.)
However, if you look in the "Napi" shopping cart, it seems almost impossible to do so in the latter case, since the price level of the product, which was already expensive in the previous year, has risen by hardly more than 10 per cent even in the worst case.
Clearly, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than the fast-moving suppliers - after all, they have been able to pass on the drastic price increase to the multinationals.
In the golden triangle of trade, hypermarkets do not complain; good years are reported all the time.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores no longer look at the prices.
They buy in large quantities from all kinds of foodstuffs, and they sell them on pallets.
On Wednesday morning, all three department stores were in endless lines at the checkout, when suddenly the number of customers exploded.
However, the country reports a lower frequency of customers, so many multinationals complain to opinion pollsters that they cannot even achieve the sales they planned, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
In many places, disinfectants are being saved
More than a thousand infections in hospitals were recorded this year as a result of improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overloading of staff - all factors that are not particularly conducive to curbing infections, says the chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, savings are also made on disinfectants.
A MRSA infection was recently diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was admitted to hospital after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
There was a similar infection earlier this year.
The injured man of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but soon afterwards the man had to return with an MRSA infection.
By December 10, 1,094 infections caused by multi-drug resistant pathogens had been reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System from hospitals, according to Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been reported in hospitals, but the unknown number is likely to be higher.
Approximately two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium is carried by about a third of people in their noses without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as strep throat, tonsillitis, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics and are easily curable.
However, if the drugs are used too heavily or inadequately, the bacteria that respond well to antibiotics become resistant and can spread rapidly in hospitals under the right conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened or permanently dysfunctional immune systems, but also in the elderly or in patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infections or blood poisoning, or sepsis.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, MRSA infection is not a special case, such incidents are part of the daily life of the hospital.
Infection should not be confused with epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA does not exist only where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff wear rubber gloves and masks when they are treated, and we have the antibiotics needed for treatment", says Tibor Nyulasi.
Although patients are tested for MRSA upon admission to hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rarely
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavourable for curbing the emergence or spread of the multi-drug resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection is predominantly found in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine the patients admitted and isolate MRSA-infected patients immediately.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, microbiological sampling is not as commonly practiced.
Not least because the state health insurance fund does not provide any funding for this study.
Most cases, therefore, do not come to light until the patient has a noticeable MRSA infection, says the medical director of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but in Hungary there are also guidelines on the treatment of certain infections and pathologies.
Antibiotic therapies are intended to be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the agent, but hospitals do not always comply with this directive.
Among outpatients or those in primary care, microbiological sampling is even rarer, says Karolina Böröcz.
The savings are made on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by caregivers.
This is why handwashing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but domestic hospitals do not always have the ability to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often crowded, the beds are close together, although epidemiologically speaking, they should be separated by at least 1.5 metres.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, in the less financially well-off hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are saved, there are fewer nurses, many patients - all factors that almost favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections have been shown to be much less frequent, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
MRSA infections are costing health insurance companies a lot of money to control, so they're being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its control, was included in the government programme.
Initial indications are that the programme is successful - published data show that the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has identified the prevention of the development of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
The death-link police chief wasn't drunk.
The official report on the fatal car accident caused by the police chief of the 22nd district has now been issued.
The now-retired police chief of the XXII district, who killed a pedestrian in a car crash on Tuesday, was neither drunk nor under the influence of drugs, said Attila Morvai, the spokesman for the Budapest prosecutor's office, on Friday, after the official report on the case was presented.
The report confirmed the results of the preliminary investigation, according to which the police chief had not consumed alcohol before he took the wheel.
The former police chief drove his own car into Kossuth Lajos Street in the XXII district and ran over a 55-year-old man who was crossing the street at an unmarked spot.
(According to the StVO, this is not a mitigating circumstance - the steering wheel is secondary even if pedestrians do not cross the road on the zebra strip.)
The pedestrian died of his injuries after being admitted to hospital.
According to police reports, the driver suffered a shock, resigned from his duties and requested retirement.
The Budapest prosecutor's office has opened an investigation into the incident.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former police chief had cooperated with the investigators from the beginning.
EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements worth a total of EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday, to be used for education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework in 2006 to finance transport and environmental protection projects with Cohesion Fund grants. e loan agreement of EUR 100 million was signed earlier, and the current agreement concerns the use of the EUR 200 million granted.
The EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement is also to be used for the budgetary financing of education projects.
The EIB has committed a total of EUR 300 million to Hungary for this purpose; the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later in the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement for EUR 50 million, which will be mainly used for research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
The meeting also discussed the 4 line of the metro.
It was agreed that once Hungary had clarified the details of the financing of the metro with the EU, the original contract and any modifications would be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed 113 projects in Hungary, totalling EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest rates are linked to EURIBOR and the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, without commissions.
Bulgaria, the real estate haven of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all Europe is looking attentively at the previously rarely mentioned Balkan country.
What, where and who is buying in the EU's still cheapest market, but rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most sought-after place to buy property in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and seaside homes.
Among the mountains, the most popular are the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa, while the seaside regions include Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar, the racetrack, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik is also increasingly in demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior will attract investors sooner or later, for example Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and the extremely favorable area of Russe also shows more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers attractive offers - commercial and office space offers the highest returns.
Bulgaria is well on its way to becoming one of the most attractive golfing destinations in Europe, attracting tourists in the summer and winter seasons as well as in the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy property in Bulgaria are also looking for a change in their lifestyle.
The majority of buyers are English, but there are also interested buyers from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down buy either revitalized properties for 50 to 100,000 euros, or run-down houses for 5 to 15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility and communication are important, but proximity to a major city, shops and doctors are also crucial for buyers.
The second category includes those looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations for Germans in December).
The third group is businessmen who invest with the aim of increasing value in the medium to long term.
The capital city is also experiencing a steady increase in the price of real estate, due to the ever-increasing demand.
Although Bulgaria has the lowest property prices in the EU, it has seen a 21% increase in prices over the past five years.
The increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian six per cent
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue with the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the expiry of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is a heated debate going on between the industrialized and developing countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but is willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020 compared with 1990.
The other big question of the conference is whether the developed countries are prepared to provide both financial and technological support to the developing countries in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on aid to developing countries.
The Kyoto Protocol's adaptation fund is to be managed by a Council of 16, presumably under the auspices of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as can be seen in Piace et Profit.
Hungary's six percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to remain at the forefront of global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (compared to 1990 levels), whether or not the "Post-2012 Agreement" is achieved, and that the Union would even be ready to commit to a 30% reduction if other major industrial countries in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to meet their commitments in a responsible and efficient manner.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the goal of the countries that had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, whereas the EU, with its then 15 Member States, had already committed to a reduction of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared with 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, as can be seen in the press release from the Ministry of Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012 - in which case the reduction plans set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed by a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which was also highlighted by the IPCC, the international climate change scientific committee of the UN, which won the Nobel Peace Prize in its recent report.
This would delay emissions reductions and inevitably increase the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C, with consequences that scientists say are extremely serious and irreparable.
British Army is advertising on YouTube
British Army units have posted footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to the video portal to boost its popularity.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube for itself: Special Forces in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The footage, taken with miniature cameras mounted on helmets, is checked at Kandahar Air Force Base and then sent to London, where it is uploaded to the Internet.
Political message is inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, and their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The UK Ministry of Defence registered under 'defenceheadquarters' in spring 2007 to publish videos of Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the UK Foreign Office (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peace Keeping Force (MNFI) stationed in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
The Air Force originally published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and the Department of Defense says the posts also serve to inform the public about the real goals of foreign missions.
Such published propaganda is almost free compared to traditional television advertisements, said defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message, as they confirm the legitimacy of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans are advertising with games
The army also has to fight against amateur film, which, alongside carefully edited, censored footage, also makes it to the net - such as those showing the deaths of soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the casualties are the main topic, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Incidentally, many videos of the war in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genre" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, with the free-to-download shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's shoes in a more or less lifelike simulation.
