More and more forces mobilized for giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Federation of Trade Unions are forming their coordinating committee for the indefinite strike starting on Monday.
On Saturday a protest rally is held, and on Monday - the day of the referendum on the Health Insurance Act - the lay-off begins.
The strike is expected to cause significant traffic disruption, as rail traffic will be almost completely halted and Budapest's public transport companies (BKVs) will also be on strike until 1 p.m.
Details of the strike on Monday will be announced jointly by the League of Trade Unions and the Federation of Trade Unions on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA-MOSZ strike committee will also be set up to coordinate the actions on Monday.
A protest rally will be held on Saturday and from Monday all organisations that have joined the strike will stop working indefinitely unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike, which began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the health insurance law, was not defined.
If the National Council does not pass the health insurance law, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike action.
If the law is passed, however, the strike committees meet to discuss the next steps.
The agenda of the National Council on Monday makes it even conceivable that it will not come to a vote on the Health Insurance Act until late in the evening or even at midnight.
The strike, which will begin on Monday, will lead to significant traffic disruptions: railway workers will stop their work indefinitely, most public transport will be shut down in the morning and more than half of Volán's companies will be shut down.
At the same time, there will be one-way roadblocks in many places.
The call for strike action has been followed by numerous trade unions and civil society organisations - the list of participants is updated on the League's website.
Some organisations have announced indefinite strikes, others are planning temporary layoffs.
As of Thursday afternoon, no agreement had been reached between the Hungarian Railway MÁV and the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers VDSZSZ on adequate services, although more and more people are travelling by train around Christmas.
According to reports, the BKVs are on strike from the start of the day until 1 p.m., at Budapest Airport between 7 and 9 a.m., the LIGA Electricity and Heating Unions are on strike for four hours, and the teachers' union, for example the Democratic Teachers' Union, have called for 2- and 2-8 hour strikes.
The Hungarian Medical Association is striking at different times in alternation throughout the country, the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organisation of the SZEF, the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraw the draft reform of the health insurance system and submit a new concept for the social discourse.
The second requirement concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due from next year.
The third requirement is that eligible occupational groups should be able to access the early retirement scheme before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which is part of the Trade Union League, has not accepted the sub-line offer submitted by the Ministry of Transport and is now calling for a new approach.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increases state risk
According to Political Capital's Risk Analysis Division, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was established in August with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, have increased the risk to Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's 'risk warning report' states, among other things, that the greatest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is the 'exacerbation of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy populations in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term'.
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is presumably aimed at provoking such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
This is reportedly seen as a failure on the part of political leaders: "Public figures have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups, who have now based their political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian antagonism".
It is suspected that this would aggravate the problem, prevent reasonable dialogue, favour extremism, and increase the likelihood of violent clashes.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention from the domestic and foreign media, have "significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We recall that since the autumn of 2006 the reorganisation of radical and extreme right groups in Hungary has been on the rise, so that since the summer of 2007 several organisations called the "National Self-Defence Association" have been established.
"The common feature of these groups is that they each define themselves as a civilian organization, while openly boasting of preparing their members for - sometimes armed - defence tasks (disaster protection, national defence, law enforcement), citing the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state itself", it said.
And further: all this is done according to the method which tries to disguise various political aspirations based on the political and party obsession of the population as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on the civil nature and the form of the association is therefore not merely a means of avoiding legal obstacles which might arise in the course of registration with the courts - it is also a political strategy.
The analysis shows that the activities of the Hungarian Guard also constitute a risk-increasing factor for relations with neighbouring countries.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighboring countries, so some ultra-nationalist politicians in certain neighboring countries see the emergence of the Hungarian Guard as confirmation of their own anti-Hungarian policies.
All this has implications for the political stability of the region".
The research institute considers that the creation of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, and that the political risk to the region as a whole has increased.
The activities of the Hungarian Guard are reportedly similar to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The background to the creation of the Bulgarian Guard was the mass riots of Roma in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took the incidents as an occasion for the creation of the National Guard, arguing that the goal of the organization was "national protection".
In their view, a veritable "gypsy terror" has been felt in Bulgaria over the past 17 years, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent, according to Political Capital.
The initiative would have sparked a heated debate among the Bulgarian public.
As I said, the increased risk of ethnic conflict is also evidenced by the fact that some Bulgarian Roma organizations have announced that they are setting up their own guards for resistance purposes.
Since the activities of the Hungarian Guard so far show many similarities to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, it cannot be ruled out that the Hungarian Roma are also responding to the threats by organizing their own protection, according to the risk warning report by Political Capital.
