Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary, public holidays are strictly regulated by law, so that the practice of rearranging working days around public holidays has become established, but we will have fewer such days next year.
The European Union and the United States also have a different definition of a holiday.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and non-working days.
The days off are usually church holidays or are associated with important historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year's Day: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are non-working days - the latter just so that New Year's Eve celebrants can rest.
We have a total of fourteen holidays throughout the year.
The state holidays are 15 March, which commemorates the 1848 Revolution, and 23 October, the anniversary of the 1956 Revolution.
On August 20th, the founding of the State is celebrated, on May 1st, work is celebrated, on November 1st and 2nd we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each - Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our public, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "workday postponement" has proved effective in cases where we would work only one day before or after the holiday.
The price of extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
The date on which this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is to be finally worked out has been determined for many years by the Minister of Labour in a regulation of his own.
The legislation applies to all employers and employees, to civil servants and civil servants alike.
Only firms and establishments where the business is carried on without interruption, i.e. also on public holidays, are excluded.
The work schedule is now only a little confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from 24 December onwards, life in this country is formally at a standstill, as most people take the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve in the same time, or the holidays set aside for that purpose.
Next year, more holidays will fall in the middle of the week or at the end of the week, so there will be less reordering of working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the workday so that people can stay home for four days straight.
Saturday, April 26, will be a working day so that Friday, May 2, can be a day of rest.
The second change is linked to the holiday of 23 October: on Saturday 18 October, the work will have to be carried out in advance on Friday 24 October.
The end of the year will be marked by holidays, however, since everything will be in place from 24 December, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
