A painful memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now open to the public.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, have so far been unable to be accessed except for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individual and named, i.e. upon request of a former victim or his relatives.
The 11 countries responsible for its administration - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to make it available to researchers and historians.
The opening of the procedure is effective since yesterday, following the completion of the ratification process of this Decision.
The Commission
The historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to conduct research, "especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps and the health of forced labourers", explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several countries, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The lists of concentration camp inmates or the Gestapo warrants for their arrest were compiled after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labor and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent staff in Bad Arolsen are still processing tens of thousands of personal requests.
However, there is a part of the scientific community that shows only limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents", declared Professor Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Centre for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
