Congress approves the MIFID directive, which went into effect on November 1.
In parallel with the parliamentary work, which ended today with the Senate's congressional resolution on the supplementary/amendment motions related to the project, the government published the provisions resulting from the new law, with the intention of allowing the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously commended the efforts of the members of the Congress and the Senate, who in their negotiations and votes had sought to establish the best possible arrangements to ensure the safety of investors and to regulate the individual activities of entrepreneurs in order to guarantee an overall efficient market.
In addition to modernising financial markets, MIFID, which redefines the rules governing investment services, aims to improve investor protection, increase the supervisory authority of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive allows financial advice to be provided to both specialist firms and natural or legal persons and also contributes to the creation of new financial services firms (ESIS), advisory firms which join investment and intermediary firms.
It also expands the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions, adding to the regulated markets multilateral systems for the trading of securities and systems for the internationalisation of trading orders, which would eventually compete with the current economic operators.
The law requires investment firms to disclose the main features of their business profile, the way they deal with and manage risks on the market and to register all projects carried out, thus facilitating the CNMV's control tasks.
The Congressional Economic Committee subsequently made further changes, with the decision that securities must now be considered as "complex" financial instruments because of their high degree of risk to the investor, confirmed by the US mortgage and banking crisis. (US mortgage crisis)
The Commission has also taken advantage of the entry into force of the Directive on the legal limitation of the fields of work of graduate economists, 30 years after the 1977 Regulation limiting the fields of work reserved for economists.
The Senate also defined new positions in the financial sector, such as that of an economic intermediary who operates on behalf of others, does not require authorisation from the CNMV and can offer his services for the commercialisation of products and the acquisition of clients to several investment firms at the same time.
