A new price dispute is raging between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk that Russian fuel exports to Western Europe will be affected.
The bulk of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are through Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will be charged higher transit fees by Russia.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced shipments to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine will have to be charged more as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% extra for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for Gazprom's imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the main transit countries in talks", Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
"The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine".
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut supplies to Ukraine.
This led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drove prices up sharply.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom is supplementing its own gas reserves with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
