The climate on Venus could give a glimpse of the future of the Earth
Venus may once have been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit show that the planet is even more like an Earth-like twin than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are roughly the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Billions of years ago, Venus would have been in conditions very similar to those on Earth, and scientists now believe that it might even have been habitable.
But because of the unchecked greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation, and a slower rate of rotation, Venus took a very different course of evolution.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead and is being devastated by hurricane-force winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, which has studied the planets for a year, offer a sobering look at how the Earth might evolve in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, whereas the planets are otherwise quite similar".
"Our new data allows us to construct a scenario where Venus began billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment".
