Giuliani is trying to shake off the reputation that he was lenient with illegal immigration when he was mayor of New York.
He attacked Romney in which he accused the former governor of Massachusetts of hiring illegal immigrants to work on his house.
The two were particularly bitter when the questioner asked whether either candidate would support an "amnesty" (which would give illegal immigrants a regular status and the possibility of citizenship).
Minority candidates, such as Duncan Hunter, a congressman from California, and Tom Tancredo, a congressman from Colorado, were able to catch up on the issue.
Neither of these men has a serious chance at the nomination, but they both stay in the race, perhaps because they've hit the immigration loop harder and earlier than others.
At least on the immigration front, the candidates share broadly the same views: tighter borders, intolerance of illegal immigrants.
This issue, along with fears about toxic toys from China or other concerns about the rest of the world, helps Republicans forget or minimize the differences between liberals and Christian conservatives.
But the debate was clearly problematic when other issues were brought up.
Mr Giuliani was asked why he had supported gun restrictions in the past.
John McCain and Romney discussed whether simulated drowning should be considered torture.
One of the interviewers asked whether the candidates believed every word of the Bible.
