Another questioner asked whether Jesus supported the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee - now, against all odds, ranked first in a recent Iowa poll thanks to his longstanding Christian conservatism - said the death penalty was painful but necessary.
When pressed on whether Jesus would endorse her, he laughed and said that Jesus was too intelligent to run for political office.
The race remains exceptionally wide open.
Huckabee's rise in Iowa coincides with Ron Paul's recent fundraising successes and his thunderous applause in Wednesday's debate.
These two have been thrown up out of nowhere because the two wings of the party have not yet been able to agree on one of the more well-known and traditional candidates.
In 1980 and 2000, one candidate has united the party from the beginning and convincingly with a victorious message about the greatness of America and a wink to both wings of the party.
This time the party is divided and the result is far from clear.
Labour Party pain
Gordon Brown has discovered yet another pit to fall into; his way out of this remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not particularly slippery.
No titles of nobility seem to have been sold, no politicians paid Paris hotel bills, no extra-marital toes have been licked.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman had been hiding donations to the British ruling Labour Party of more than 650,000 pounds ($1.3 million) over four years under other people's names, and that the party had failed to report this, is something that the contender Gordon Brown would have done well without.
When the Prime Minister two months ago refused to call an election, foolishly insulting the intelligence of the British people by claiming that opinion polls had no bearing on that decision, there was hope that he would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly perceptive chairman of the Liberal Democrats, put it, the once-feared Brown has gone from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a struggling bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to change tax laws have angered business associations against the government.
The loss of personal data of 25 million people by the tax authorities revealed unimaginable administrative fraud.
A trio of retired generals started a revolt in the House of Lords against military spending cuts, claiming that being Minister of Defence was a part-time job.
Now there are the multiple donations from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's general secretary (and its former head of fulfillment) has already resigned.
None of this means Brown is going to resign.
Yet governments may reach a turning point where they feel that they cannot govern.
People may not trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it's clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he doesn't even need to be around for long, that delay is over: the public service starts leaking; the cabinet ministers start babbling; the press searches for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown's position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he'd like to deny Tony Blair, he was his first lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction files, for example, are related to decisions Brown made as Chancellor of the Exchequer.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blair's misadventures - as in the long "money for titles" investigation of political party funding - voters may assume he was.
Still, Brown's situation isn't quite as bad as it looks.
The mistakes are not as terrible as the conservatives describe them.
Like Mr. Bean, no one died or was completely swindled.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown's naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new wave of political donations is a good example.
The scumbag Abraham, who compares his donations to his charitable giving, says he does not want public recognition for his benevolence.
That may be true, but it was not his decision.
The laws against anonymity for big political contributors are clear, and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham's deal but not that it was illegal, will of course have to ask some questions, just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour's chief financial officer, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far, Brown is not involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He was quick to condemn the violation of the law by his party, but he watered down that determination by resorting to a well-known instrument, a committee of inquiry into the matter - led to the full measure, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "lessons to be learned" are not very complicated.
If the law was broken, it's a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things Mr Brown has to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the independent committee on standards in public life, which has been vacant for six months, and moving forward with a sweeping reform of political party funding.
This would require the hardliners of Labour to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly to abandon the special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a Party member like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some biased facts.
The Conservatives are now clearly ahead in the polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can achieve a victory is through unchallenged integrity and solid competence.
