Is the credit crisis affecting America's credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, it's only natural for the dorsal fin to spin around excitedly.
Now that America's housing market is in decline, predators are targeting the nation's credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if the risk of underfunded credit spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both write-downs and default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are either non-recoverable or more than 30 days late.
HSBC announced last month that it had taken a $1.4 billion charge from its U.S. consumer finance, in part because of the weakness of credit cardholders.
It's still too early to panic.
Losses and casualties are still low.
According to Moody's, the third-quarter seed rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in US private bankruptcy law in 2005 led to a sharp fall in bankruptcy filings, which again account for a large proportion of credit card losses; the number of filings (and thus default fees) would rise again whether or not the general conditions for borrowers deteriorate.
The industry also reports solid payment rates, which show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month
And confidence in credit card-based securities is pretty strong, despite the stagnation in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup, a research firm, expects that spending volumes for 2007 will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct infection channels between the housing credit crisis and the credit card market: consumers are more likely to take on credit card debt as home loans dry up.
However, card issuers look at cash flow rather than capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower's creditworthiness.
They can even be of benefit to the card issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage rates decrease when the real estate is worth less than the value of the loan, and as a result card debt becomes more important among repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also respond to the more volatile conditions much more quickly and flexibly than lenders by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of the assets.
"We're not going to wake up one day and completely revaluate the loans", says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
Even if a sudden credit card market underwriting crisis is unlikely, the risks of a sustained downturn are much more real.
If lower house prices and credit reduction push America into recession, industry will no doubt face a grimmer future.
Keep an eye out for those shark fins.
British bankers plead guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who were due to stand trial for their role in the fraudulent scheme with former Enron chief financial officer Andrew Fastow changed their pleas to guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had originally pleaded not guilty to seven counts of wire fraud for allegedly conspiring with Fastow in a secret financial fraud in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of their employer.
The procedure had been scheduled for January.
But during a court hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., each pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud.
The three former senior executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, came to light in the UK during two years of extradition proceedings.
In the United States, her case is the loose end of an investigation that began after Enron's collapse in 2001.
The charges initially brought against her in 2002 brought Fastow to the attention of the public that he was the target of a government investigation in connection with the Enron collapse.
The indictment against the bankers, known as the NatWest Three, alleges that they came to Houston in 2000 to plot a fraudulent scheme with Fastow and his former top adviser Michael Kopper.
Greenwich Natwest had invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partnership controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of countless fraudulent Enron schemes that helped to drive the company into bankruptcy.
At the beginning of 2002, the Bank had estimated the value of its holding in the subsidiary at zero, but the three British men knew that it was in fact of considerable value.
A company under Kopper's control bought the bank's shares in the subsidiary for $1 million.
The bankers paid Copper $250,000 for a stake in this company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely represented to Enron that the energy company would pay 20 million dollars to Greenwich NatWest for its stake in the subsidiary.
But in fact, the $20 million went to the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers received $7.3 million, while Fastow, Copper and others withheld about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy for his role in the Enron bankruptcy.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year sentence at the Louisiana State Penitentiary.
Copper is serving a three-year, one-month sentence in a facility in Texarkana.
Each of the three men was free on a $1 million bond, which required them to live in the United States pending trial.
Enron, once the nation's seventh-largest company, collapsed in bankruptcy in December 2001, after years of accounting tricks could no longer mask the billions in debt or make weakening businesses look profitable.
The collapse wiped out thousands of jobs, more than $60 billion in market value, and more than $2 billion in pension plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the Enron collapse.
Skilling is serving a sentence of over 24 years.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud and other charges were overturned after he died of heart disease last year.
Not down in Moscow
The price of a Gulfstream G550 aircraft, equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and with enough range to fly nonstop from Moscow to Los Angeles, is at least $54 million.
But that's a small amount of money for some of the rich Russians.
"It can seat up to 18 passengers", said Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
"But none of you are asking for that many seats because it's for a private family or a corporate president".
Firer was at the Gulfstream stand last Friday at the Millionaire Exhibition, a four-day orgy of show-business consumption held in a nested exhibition center on the outskirts of the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, more than 200 other luxury suppliers had set up booths, hoping to attract newly-income Russians to everything from mahogany-plated yachts to diamond-coated car grills that would be reasonable for 50 cents.
Firer cautiously targeted a shiny orange Porsche at the next stand.
"It's a nice car, but it's small money compared to us", he said.
"Russia is the second largest market for private jets after the United States".
Fueled by an oil boom, the Russian capital seems as flooded with money as Dallas was in its heyday.
"We went through the same phase in the 1890s when some Americans got enormous wealth and went in droves to Europe, where they were considered materialistic", said Marshall Goldman, a scholar at the Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies at Harvard University.
Like the Saudi Arabian flyovers of the 1970s and the Japanese in the 1990s, the Russians are emerging as the most visible and generous money spenders in the world.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking to take their share of the gold rush.
Elsewhere in Moscow, a conference of the luxury industry this week attracted Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, the chairman of LVMH, to exchange ideas on how to sell high-priced goods in markets like Russia.
(The conference is organized by The International Herald Tribune, which is owned by the New York Times Company.)
Russia has 53 billionaires who have a total of $282 billion, according to Forbes' list of the richest people.
Moreover, 103,000 Russian millionaires are in the second class, worth a total of $670 billion, according to a study on the development of private wealth in the former Soviet Union, written by economists at the Center for Economic and Financial Research, a think tank here.
(The World Bank says that in 2005 15.8 percent of Russians lived below the minimum.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow - that's why we're all here", said Nicole Marais, a sales and marketing representative for David Morris, a London jeweler.
She had first visited the fair together with the Russian retailer of the brand, Soho Jewelry Group.
"The women are all well-groomed and the men are all worth a fortune".
As they walk through the halls Sunday night in evening clothes, two real estate agents, Evgenia Yumatova, 21, and Svetlana Turovtsova, 26, call themselves and their clients millionaires.
"I've been looking at the cars and I'm trying to decide between the Infiniti, the Mercedes and the Porsche", said Ms. Yumatova, who delivered the designer clothes she wore, like a red carpet veteran with Joan Rivers.
The show seemed primarily aimed at the newly rich, the type of brand-conscious Russian buyers who would be willing to stand in traffic for hours to visit a swollen warehouse that shamelessly stacked Cadillac Escalades, platinum pocket knives, Mövenpick ice cream, custom-made billiard tables, apartments in Dubai and Gund Teddy bears.
Tickets were available for the public for 30 euros ($44.57).
"The Russians are interested in learning which brand is the most expensive and the best", said Mr. Gijrath, who sat patriotically at a booth of the Dutch porcelain manufacturer Royal Delft in front of a wall-sized imitation of a Rembrandt painting made of hand-painted blue mosaics.
"Of course, the Russians are more interested in clippers".
In fact, the dealers here say that Russians with old money (10 to 15 years old by Russian standards) have already moved from big-time logos to the kind of sober brands with limited numbers that wouldn't be marketed at a trade show.
Nevertheless, thousands of people, whether millionaires, millionaire envoys, or tourists, poured through the halls every day.
And some of them bought.
On the first night of the show last Thursday, Roman Ershov, the general manager of King Koil Beds here, said he had sold two $70,000 mattress sets made of silk, cashmere and cotton, sewn with gold threads.
Also on the first night, Mikhail Lyubiumov, a sales manager for A1 Moto, a company that equips high-end cars with high-end alarm systems, said his company sold the bright orange Porsche for $170,000 to a Russian millionaire.
By Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a company that customizes luxury cars, said he had sold three car radiators for a Rolls-Royce Phantom that resemble interlocking chain-arm tires for $55,000 each.
He showed a reporter a tire designed for a Russian casino owner, with spokes he had coated with colored Swarovski crystals, so it looked like a roulette wheel.
The cost: $22,000 for a four-piece.
"The Russian millionaire who wants ostrich leather wheels or a picture of his wife's face made of cubic zirconium will not necessarily ride on these wheels", Mr Karapetian said.
"He'll keep it in his garage of 30 or 40 cars".
Although many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian said the phrase "Russian millionaires" would not express much exclusivity at the moment, given the rise in local property prices.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already a millionaire, at least on paper, if not in cash", he said.
"There are more of them than you think".
Those who were not millionaires could at least pretend to be rich at a stand operated by Alliance Continental, a Russian asset management firm.
The company had set up four red telephone booths, modeled after British ones, filled with piles of counterfeit million-dollar bills.
Azad Karryev, the company's marketing director, said his employees had printed 500,000 fake bills for the millionaire's fair.
Passersby stopped to throw money piles around, cell phone photos while reclining amidst the surplus wealth, getting their hair cut by friends, or just to get a few million.
"Look, in Moscow, everyone can feel like a millionaire", Mr. Karryev said.
Suspected malfunction in New Jersey death
It was the day before Thanksgiving when Ronald Livingston looked out the big glass window of the Just a Little Healthier restaurant here and watched as an ambulance on the white Cape Cod stopped two doors down on West Scott Avenue.
Soon a police car was there.
And then there was another one.
"Then I saw the medical examiner's boxcar coming", said Livingston, a restaurant supervisor, on Wednesday.
"That's when I knew someone had died".
The authorities learned that the dead woman was Olga Arroyo, 41, an assistant to the director of the Newark Police Department.
Now, investigators are trying to determine if she died from a procedure performed by an unlicensed cosmetic surgeon, whom police have not identified, who worked at the house at 212 West Scott Avenue.
Authorities have yet to determine what caused Ms. Arroyo's death, and are hopeful that toxicology tests, the results of which may not be available for weeks, will help unravel a mysterious death that has sent mourning through the top of Newark police.
Ms. Arroyo had been an assistant to Police Chief Garry F. McCarthy since September 2006, and her voice was familiar to many in the department.
"She was loyal, hardworking and tenacious", Mr McCarthy said of Ms Arroyo in a telephone interview on Wednesday.
"She was my pit bull.
She protected me".
McCarthy said that Mrs. Arroyo was the wife of Jimmy Arroyo, a former Newark police officer who works for the Alcohol Control Board, and that she left behind two sons, 14 and 11, and a stepdaughter.
Eileen Walsh, a spokeswoman for Union County Prosecutor Theodore J. Romankow, said investigators are trying to determine whether Arroyo died as a result of an unauthorized surgical treatment.
"That's one way", said Mrs. Walsh.
"It's an ongoing investigation".
Authorities said they arrived at the house around 3:00 p.m. in November.
And they found Mrs. Arroyo on a couch.
She was pronounced dead at the scene.
More than a week has passed and the authorities have given little notice of their investigation or of the owner of the house, who is listed as Flor Margarita Castro.
Walsh wouldn't say if Mrs. Castro was questioned by the authorities.
Investigators are trying to determine if any part of the house was used as a medical practice.
On Wednesday, no one opened the door to Mrs. Castro's house, where a withered rose bush stands in the narrow front yard and a Dalmatian barks behind the house.
A blue barrel labeled "ethyl vanillin" - used as a substitute for vanilla in food and perfume - sat in the parking lot next to a door leading to the basement.
Two mountain bikes were hanging from hooks on one side.
McCarthy said that when he first arrived in Newark after 25 years with the New York Police Department, Ms. Arroyo was invaluable in helping him adjust to the provincial and harsh political culture of his new city.
"She said, 'You have to pay attention to this or that,'" he said.
"She was always here when I came here and she was always here when I left.
It was embarrassing".
Hopes that the central bank will cut interest rates will lead to a rise in world stock markets
Stocks jumped on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday, after market hopes that the Fed would try to calm credit markets by further interest rate cuts were bolstered by soothing comments from the vice chairman of the Fed.
Stock markets rose in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kahn, the number two of Ben Bernanke, the chairman of the central bank, said that policy must be "flexible and pragmatic" in response to the continued pressure on financial markets.
In a clear effort to calm down frenetic markets in the face of signs of rising credit tensions, Kohn said the recent turmoil had "partly reversed some of the improvements in market performance from the latter part of September and October".
The Commission's proposal for a directive on the protection of consumers' rights in the event of a serious accident, which is not covered by the directive, is not yet in force.
The comments were taken by investors as a signal that the central bank was ready to step in and stabilise credit conditions with new capital injections into US markets and possible further interest rate cuts.
The comments also helped calm Wall Street in the face of further bad news from the US economy, now that US property sales hit a new record low in October.
The impact of the financial turmoil was underscored by the announcement by Bear Stearns, the investment bank, that it would eliminate 650 jobs, or 4 percent of its global workforce, in a cost-cutting measure to offset heavy losses from its lost bets in the U.S. mortgage lending sector.
Only 20 of these jobs are expected to disappear in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 331 points, or 2.55 percent, to close at 13,289.40, while the broader S&P 500 index rose 2.65 percent.
In London, the FTSE 100 index rose 165.5 points, or 2.7 percent, to close at 6,306.2, adding more than 39 billion pounds to the value of British standard values.
Germany's Dax index rose by 2.6 per cent and France's CAC40 rose by 2.3 per cent.
The re-emergence of credit pressure on markets had previously been highlighted after strong demand for three-month European Central Bank guarantee funds granted to European commercial banks was awarded at a considerable 4.7%, the highest rate since April 2001.
Pressure on the Bank of England, the US central bank and the European central bank to follow suit and to infuse more capital into the money markets in London increased as credit tensions saw the three-month "Libor" rates on borrowing between UK banks rise to their highest since late September at 6.59 percent, after a continuous rise since 21 November.
England faced with decision on Owais Shah and Ravi Bopara's testimony
Here are two dilemmas, each almost as difficult as the other.
Who's going to be the number six for England in Kandy this weekend, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, no less relevant in a broader context than the first Test against Sri Lanka, who is to make the decision?
The second question is important because David Graveney, the chairman of the Electoral Commission, is here on call, at least under this particular title, to help head coach Peter Moores and captain Michael Vaughan decide, and because the desk of High Morries, the English chief executive, is gradually filling up with applications for national electorates, if not even part-time ones.
Whoever doesn't get the sixth batting position will be unhappy, but life is often unfair and sport is undoubtedly.
It is never easy to pinpoint exactly what enables one person to reach the top of his or her profession, while another never gets beyond the lowest rank, sometimes due to lack of luck rather than ability.
It's not just in cricket that the choices are difficult, that judgments are necessary, which are always subjective in the end.
Is this the right time for Bopara to ascend?
Is it fair to Shah if he does it?
The same question may be asked in another area, whether, for example, John Edwards or "Tubby" Banerjee, both intelligent young executives with good degrees and good knowledge of the business, should be promoted.
Who can tell what the right class is for a cricketer unless he is given the opportunity to swim or to sink.
Of course, numbers have a big influence on decisions, but so do opportunities.
Within a team, a cricketer must catch the eye of the captain at the right time when he can take a wicket and a batsman must get regular chances on the order if he wants to impress as a one-day cricketer.
Catching the eyes of the selectors is more complicated.
There were many who were better than, say, James Anderson last season, who is likely to play in the first Test, even if Stephen Harmison declares himself healthy and the wind is blowing in the nets.
Anderson took 32 first-class wickets at 33 runs each to earn a place in this tour.
Chris Tremlett only took 29 with the same modest average, but both had their highlights and hoped for even more.
Whether Shah or Bopara will play at Asgiriya Stadium can only be a matter of opinion.
The choice could decide the careers of both men, or it might make little difference.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, Gareth Batty played in every Test and was successful in the first, taking five wickets and 40 runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, then still struggling to establish himself, who made the breakthrough into a major Test cricketer and who, although he scored a double century against Australia in Australia, is perhaps still underrated.
It is likely that Graveney, Vaughan and Moores, after further discussion in the course of today's web session at Asgiriya Stadium, will follow their conservative instincts and gut feelings for Shah's greater experience of Bopara's youthful enthusiasm.
There are arguments for both.
Shah is best remembered for his sparkling and valuable 88 Test debut innings in Bombay, 43 first-class centuries and only six from Bopara, who is seven years his junior at 22, and an excellent balance against spin balls.
But Shah scored just ten runs in his two innings in May against the West Indies in the Test at Lord's, his home ground as a Middlesex player, and this, plus his immediate rejection by the selectors as Vaughan was healthy to take his position back for the next game, seems to have taken the momentum from his strikes, which were still evident in Bombay.
The man from Essex, on the other hand, has a shallow sense of joy.
He is not impressed by anything on a cricket field and his attitude away from it was brought to the point when he recently ran over a four-wheel-drive vehicle at an exhibition for England's sponsor Volkswagen.
He suffered minor injuries and probably a shock, but the first thing he did was to get his Vodafone (sponsored, of course) and call his teammate Alastair Cook, who was watching from a distance, and say enthusiastically, "Did you see that?"
Bopara is a much better pitcher, he's bowling his middle pace with some effect here on the pitches, which seems to suit him and he's hitting with confidence and skill.
Choosing the right man is one thing, choosing the right time is another.
Maybe that's the real art of choice.
I'm inclined to give Bopara his chance now, which doesn't mean Shah might not be in a good place if, as the Ceylon tea party suggests, he's the one who's going to play here this weekend.
Buses bring refugees back to work - and to fight Al-Qaeda
The first busloads of Iraqi refugees from Syria arrived in Baghdad yesterday, with a stream of displaced people whose funds or visas have run out, and others hoping the city will return to normal.
Some had even returned to fight the rebels who had driven them from their homes.
At Mansour Bus Station, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official government convoy of a dozen buses, the terminal was busy with refugees from Syria and Jordan returning in private transports.
"I decided to go to Syria after they killed many doctors in Baghdad", said Sabah Al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
"I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I read in the newspapers about what happened in Baghdad and how safe it would be now".
They say the Mahdi army has stopped killing people", he said, referring to the Shiite militias of militant cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, who has ordered his forces to withdraw for the time being.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite teacher from the predominantly Sunni part of Amariyah, returned with his two children because he could not renew his Syrian visa and because the Iraqi regime did not allow him to work.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariyah called him to tell him that a local, US-backed militia had helped drive Al-Qaeda out of their stronghold in the west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of the new arrivals from Jordan was the leader of a Sunni and Shiite tribe who had been driven from his home in Sleikh, north of Baghdad, by a hand grenade attack after urging his fellow citizens to fight al-Qaeda.
He had come back to fight.
"Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they had started an anti-Al-Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my boys.
That is why I returned today", said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many said they were lured by the increasing calm in the capital since the U.S. troop build-up and the growth of local "groups of concerned citizens" who are armed and working with the U.S. military to defend their neighborhoods.
But more said they had been forced home by visa problems and cash-strapped Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis had fled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, a 51-year-old father of three, expressed the general suspicion among the exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite Prime Minister, had asked the Syrian government to impose visa restrictions on the refugees in order to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people are believed to have fled the country's sectarian death squads.
"We were doing well until al-Maliki visited Syria and the government pushed to stop issuing visas to Iraqis to force them to return to Iraq", the Sunni pensioner said.
"I can't trust a government that supports the criminals who burned down my house after I left".
Part of the reason for the decline in violence is that Sunnis have been driven out of Shiite neighborhoods and vice versa, leading to the creation of many places where tensions have eased.
There are fears that a sudden influx of refugees will reignite sectarian tensions and lead to conflict.
Small Saarland, good education
The smallest federal state is a leader in vocational training and even excels in the international orientation of its universities.
Only in one area of education do the Saarland countries have the same deficit as the rest of the country.
"I told a non-Saarlander for the 50th time yesterday that we are not French" - this is the slogan the smallest of the federal states posters ironically on its 50th birthday.
France and Luxembourg play a major role in the education system of the Saarland, which is ranked fifth in the Institute of German Economics' Education Monitor Cologne (IW).
The universities have traditionally cooperated closely with the neighbouring countries.
The University of Saarbrücken was founded in 1948 by the French.
To this day, students here can complete their studies with a double or even triple degree.
The proportion of foreign students is therefore high at 15.6%.
But the Saarland also attends higher education in higher numbers than the average number of rural children - many of them without a high school diploma.
"In Saarland, the vocational education system is used", says Axel Plünnecke, education expert at the IW.
More than one in five young people acquires their qualifications at a vocational school, which means that the Saarland is more than seven percentage points above the national average.
The possibilities for combining vocational and academic training are also comparatively strong.
The number of students studying in dual programmes is the second highest in Germany in terms of population.
