Venus is the infernal twin of Earth
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: The European spacecraft "Venus Express" has detected lightning flashes in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles, just as they occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that lightning strikes on Venus.
Now the European probe Venus Express has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning on Venus shoots from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 35 miles [56 km], reports Christopher Russel of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the science magazine Nature.
The famous "origin theory" holds that lightning caused life on earth: thunderstorms in the ocean triggered reactions that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there was ever life there, it must have been there in the very early history", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is little life on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperatures of 500 degrees Celsius are sometimes observed.
"Venus may be the devil's twin to Earth, but she is a twin", Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, has taken on such a completely different development is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The launch of the Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the history of Venus exploration, since no spacecraft had been on the road since the early 1990's.
The latest research, now being presented in several Nature articles, not only underscores the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, the researchers say.
"They also show that our neighbouring planet has more in common with Earth than was initially thought", ESA said.
In addition to the already known North Pole whirlwind, the researchers found a swirl of clouds at the South Pole that rotates much faster.
The phenomenon resembles air currents in the Earth's winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-closest planet in our solar system is nearly the same mass as Earth, and at a diameter of some 12,000 miles [12,100 km], it is almost as big.
The planet, also called the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it spins much more slowly around itself: A day on Venus lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus' surface temperature is 460 degrees Celsius and its pressure is 92 bar, scientists believe that both planets formed under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained in the oceans on Earth, but on Venus it was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide on Earth is fixed in carbonate rocks, on Venus it makes up most of the atmosphere.
