After the Swedish newspaper Expressen raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 eyeglass cases, internal investigations at the Moderna Museum in Stockholm have now reached a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo boxes" that former museum director Pontus Hultén bequeathed to Moderna Museet in 1995 are copies - and probably most of the around 100 other "Stockholm-type" eyeglass cases in circulation on the international art market.
The history is tangled, a confusing interlocking of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the paper cartons of the soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These were not from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
They were not works of art, but their models, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably gave permission in 1968 to have a few wooden brillo boxes produced in Sweden, but these were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes which, at the time, were authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Stockholm type" and have rightly entered art and auction history.
Some of them have sold for over $100,000 at auctions.
The problem is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around 100 wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968 and that Warhol then left them to him.
In fact, Hulténs 105 boxes were produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
In addition to the six museum-owned brillo boxes, Lars Byström, chief curator at the Moderna Museet, has also examined three privately owned Swedish brillo boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press panels were first ground and smudged, then painted white with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, however, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press plate with a paint roll without a base - and it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's brillo boxes", says Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve. "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not reach a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibit materials".
