United Internet becomes major shareholder in Versatel
United Internet has secured a stake of more than 20 percent in the telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, the company said on Wednesday evening.
You now hold 20.05 percent of the share capital.
There had been speculation about a takeover.
The option of increasing the proportion of Versatel is left open.
The move is aimed at consolidating the German DSL market, United Internet reported.
Earlier on Wednesday, speculation had already surfaced about an entry, after Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf network operator by a further 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The money house only held the shares for a third party, the financial market said.
The day before, United Internet had already acquired a nearly 10 percent stake in the mobile phone company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch has placed 17.4 million new shares worth EUR 106.4 million.
United Internet bought 5.15 million shares of the company for 31.4 million euros.
The companies also entered into discussions on marketing cooperation for DSL and mobile products.
"We are strengthening our partnership", a United Internet spokesman explained.
The two companies have set up the joint venture MSP to take over the competitor Freenet.
For now, the two companies want to settle for a good 10 percent stake in Freenet and not use their right to take over another 18.49 percent of Freenet, United Internet said Thursday.
The two companies, however, remained open to all options, including in particular to further increase their participation in Freenet AG.
Talks between United Internet and Freenet on a strategic partnership had been concluded in mid-November.
The months-long and difficult to trace poker around Freenet is part of the consolidation of the German telecom market.
Freenet had 2.9 million mobile subscribers and 1.27 million DSL and full-line subscribers at the end of the third quarter.
The holding company of United Internet and Drillisch previously held directly 6.01% of Freenet's shares.
It was agreed that Drillisch would bring in another four per cent.
The right to buy 18.49% from the investment company Vatas had already been agreed in August.
